Kiess's founding charter prohibition against sealed warrants from predecessor authorities was a direct legislative response to the Violet Compact's sealed-warrant mechanism. The discovery during Kiess's foundation excavations of Evermeet-era artifacts bearing Conclave markings confirmed that Evermeet participated in the Compact's "resettled south" transfer apparatus. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant clause is the most explicit legislative repudiation of Compact doctrine in the five-city corridor. The Syndic Council holds the obsidian disc bearing the Conclave's triune seal under Compact Temple seal — not displayed, not destroyed, not explained — a Compact-era item managed by Compact-era discretion even in an institution that repudiated Compact law. The Temple of Concord's cautionary recitations about institutional overreach directly reference the Compact's transformation of containment doctrine into apparatus for human transfer.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's annexation negotiations were conducted under Midgaard's Compact-era governance framework, which shaped the terms available to Rakuen administrators. The Compact's "registry primacy" doctrine meant that Rakuen's pre-annexation governance instruments had to be re-entered into Midgaard's registry system to have legal standing. The Garden Ledger was established partly as a parallel record-keeping system resistant to Compact-style registry masking. Rakuen's shared-burden doctrine emerged partly as cultural resistance to the Compact's individualization of civic obligation — the Compact treated people as individual registry entries, not as community members. Annexation-era Rakuen administrators who accepted Compact-defined terms without independent record-keeping found their communities' claims harder to contest in subsequent disputes.

