Mafdet's Quarantine Ledger documentation standards were influenced by the Violet Compact's registry primacy doctrine, adapted for maritime cargo assessment. The practical hazard classification system that Mafdet developed was adopted by some Midgaard archivists as a supplementary tool for artifacts that the Compact's registry-only approach could not adequately categorize. The Shrine of the First Claw's explicit refusal to recognize sealed instruments as legally binding is partly a response to awareness of the Compact's Sealed Names apparatus. Mafdet's dual-attestation requirement emerged partly as a counter to Compact-style single-authority registry decisions: two independent witnesses who cannot both be captured by the same institutional apparatus. The Red Sand Accounts' cross-jurisdictional debt conversion uses Compact-era registry precedents to establish Mafdet-jurisdiction claims over inland debtors — a practice that Shrine adjudicators view with increasing concern.

