Khenari archivists regard the Violet Compact's Sealed Names apparatus as a fundamental violation of record integrity. A sealed name is not a record — it is the suppression of a record while maintaining the administrative trace that the suppression occurred. The nine-descent tradition's treatment of records as sacred means that the Compact's selective registry masking constitutes a form of ritual violence against the people whose names were removed. Khenari community networks in Midgaard maintain parallel records of names that appear in Compact-era restricted archives, preserved specifically to resist the masking apparatus's permanent effect. The Unindexed Years are treated by Khenari scholars as a catastrophic record gap that cannot be rationalized by governance necessity — the oaths sworn to record everything were violated, and that violation persists in the missing names.
